Text.Value: I did the right thing. I followed the code. He deserved it. They all deserved it!
You are unfit to live. I will see that you are expunged.
You stole me from my people. Gave me to that woman. Unhatched, defenceless. You let me be brought here so father could hurt me.
Attack.
I live by my own doctrine. This defines the morality of my actions.
I live by my own code, though not the one you speak of.
Such an empty and  meaningless life.
I see. You have abandoned goodness. Like you abandoned me.
He lied to you. No one is born evil.
I am not debating with a murderer. You killed those people - you will be punished.
We're not having this conversation. If you massacred those people, you must pay the price.
Right and wrong don't matter so long as you get the job done.
You are not capable of following its teachings.
Havkelaag. He brought me from the shell. Raised me quickly. Taught me to be good. But he failed me.
You would speak of punishment to me?
So you killed them?
I thought I was saving you. I had no idea what they were planning.
I could not change that, even if I wanted to.
I'm [GEN_PlayerName_c11eee1e-7815-6143-7233-f2427799fa53]. Who are you?
Then perhaps I am one of your failures.
You feel strange, don't you? That's your conscience. It's telling you to stop.
I gave you what my patron gave me - a chance at something more.
If you only think, then you do not know.
Lies. Only death can save you now.
What's the Ptarian code?

EditorData.logicalname: Not Dragonborn or Cleric of Bahamut

Text.Value: The Ptarian Code must be obeyed. This is the only way to be sure. Do you follow it?
I - I killed him. I killed all these people. I am no better than any of them.
I am Ptaris. And I am good.
Please - there is no 'good'. There is only the power one wields over others.
You - you don't look like them. You look like me. Who are you?
I try to be. For I serve a greater power - one who embodies everything good in this world.
Such evil can only be cured one way. With pain. With torment. And if that does not work - with death.
He was not righteous. He was not innocent. His thoughts were impure.
Your gut cannot be trusted. That is why the code exists. That is why you failed.
The Ptarian code? Then you follow the teachings of Bahamut?
Then your code is flawed. Your actions cannot be defended.
It's nice to see you again, githyanki.
Father was bad. They all were. I tried to make them better, but they were not strong enough. They lacked resolve.
It is honour. Justice. The true form of goodness we all must live by, decreed by Bahamut himself.
I should feel better now. Why don't I feel better?
I see it. Your head is filled with evil. There is no goodness there.
You would have been destroyed if not for me. I saved you.
You mean anger is not always bad? But - but that's not what father said.
Cured? You still look like a githyanki to me.
You cannot be both good and bad. It is impossible. There is no goodness in you.
What have I done...?
I've tried to be, though I've failed often enough.
Who was your father?
But - but why would he hurt me if I didn't need to be cured?
Depends on how you define 'good'.
There is no 'try'. You are either good or you are not.
Probe the boy's mind.
Father saved me. I was a nasty, evil thing, but his treatments made me good. I - I'm cured.

EditorData.NodeContext: Still aggressive, but with a hint of uncertainty

Text.Value: Was Lady Esther bad too?
Ungrateful yank. Our kin would have destroyed you if it wasn't for me.
I will be the judge of that, boy. Explain yourself.
What did they do that was so terrible?
The code is flawed. And I am a monster, as he said I was. I cannot be trusted.
Evil can never save good. But good can cure evil. I will save you yet.
You are too young to be here alone. Where is your crèche?
A githyanki? What are you doing down here?
What is this place?
Are you responsible for that massacre I just walked through?
I abandoned such silly moral codes a little while ago. It's liberating.
I do not seek right or wrong. I seek balance.
I know of it. All such codes require self-discipline. In all such codes, murder is a violation.
I'm [GEN_PlayerName_c11eee1e-7815-6143-7233-f2427799fa53]. Who are you?
I wield my anger like a blade, but it does not rule me. I am no more 'bad' than you are.
So that is why you did it.
I follow my gut. That's all anyone can do.
At least you are honest.
The purest of your rulers. But you are nothing like him. You are tainted.
You were cured of nothing. Only a true githyanki would destroy their enemy so thoroughly.
Who are you? Another who needs to learn the difference between right and wrong?

EditorData.CinematicNodeContext:
The player emerges from the strange portal. They see Ptaris stood at the end of the wooden pier projecting out into the basement. He stands with his back to the player, perfectly still. At his feet is the body of Esther the expeditioner. As he speaks he turns to face the player.

Esther the expeditioner: S_GLO_Expeditioner_5f4048ba-72ef-43c2-9528-1c9a12f3f82f

Text.Value: Do not demand answers of me, yank. Tell me what happened here.
Good people offer forgiveness to those who sin. Not death.
She did not have the strength to be good. She was another like father - lacking in moral fibre.

EditorData.CinematicNodeContext: Ptaris looks down, as though only just remembering Esther lies dead at his feet.
EditorData.NodeContext: Indifferent to the dead body at his feet.

Text.Value: It is not my fault they died. I was only upholding father's code. Even he was not strong enough to follow it.
A githyanki raised in isolation. His blood boils like Vlaakith's, but he knows nothing of the Protocols.
Tell me - are you a good person?
I try not to look at things as good or evil. Life is a mixture of both.
Morality stems from choice, not doctrine.
No one code can define goodness. It's impossible.
The code of Bahamut. His guidance leads me in all things.
I fight, eat, drink, love, and hate with everything I have - that is all that matters.
Don't worry - I'm not here to judge.
My - my what?
I like to think so.
I know what you did to me. I see the memory of it, right there in your head.
I am not a githyanki. Do not call me that!

EditorData.NodeContext: Frantic- associates this word with the pain of his 'treatment'.

Text.Value: Not especially.
No - that's not why I did it. He was bad. I - I thought he deserved it.
They did not live up to father's code. Even he did not follow it correctly.
No. You have to know right from wrong. Good from bad.
My oath helps me decide right from wrong - I need no teaching.
It is my home, of course. Father raised me here. Taught me. Made me grow.
I'm good at being bad. Does that count?
I will cleanse the evil from you. Your nature can be changed. I -

EditorData.CinematicNodeContext: The boy puts both palms to his head, as though in distress.

Text.Value: Oh, no. I'm the worst.
Yet you have killed, many times. It is engraved on your memories. You are a hypocrite.
Only a bad person would say that. And that's what you are.
*A githyanki youth, and a familiar one at that. Can it be that this is the one who hatched from the egg you took from the crèche?*
I never should have saved you. But I'm happy to rectify my mistake.
Perhaps it is easier to be good when you are alone.
You've never seen another githyanki before?
No! No! Do not touch my thoughts. They are good. I am GOOD!

EditorData.NodeContext: Agonized - his mind has been tormented by his 'father' Havkelaag

Text.Value: You were trying to save me? I - I don't understand.
He is lost. A shame - he could have proved a great ally to Orpheus.
A githyanki raised in isolation. His blood boils like his kin's, but their ways are foreign.
His mind is forever lost. Come - he is no use to us, nor our queen.
His mind is forever lost. Come - he is no use to us, nor my queen.
You are bad. You must be taught a lesson.

EditorData.CinematicNodeContext: Psionic energy begins to build around the boy. He is about to attack.
EditorData.NodeContext: Like this is the onyl reasonable conclusion

Text.Value: I try to be, but sometimes my magic has other ideas.
You're right. You're right.
No. Everyone must learn. Right from wrong. Good from bad.
Father said I lacked a conscience. He said I was a nasty, evil thing, but he could make me good. He cured me.
Everyone judges, and everyone must be judged. This is the only way to know if we are good enough. Father was not.
Do you really believe that? You are unfit to say his name.
Your mind. Evil writhes within it. You cannot be cured. You must be destroyed.
There is only one way. The Ptarian code. Do you follow it?
Let him do it.
What have I done...?

Synopsis: Dialog file for Ptaris, the Gith born from the egg given to Esther. The player enters on a scene of devestation, Ptaris the only being still alive. Hatched unnaturally from his egg and experimented on in the name of making him 'good', he has developed uncanny psionic powers, and used them to murder everyone who failed to live up to his strict moral code.
